Release 057 (7/30/2014) -PPU is now pixel accurate. Meaning that many glitchy games are now completely fixed. However it also means that performance is worse. -MMC3 and MMC5 scanline counters have been rewritten to be more accurate. Fixed games: -Marble Madness -Laser Invasion -Mickey's Adventures in Letterland -Rad Racer -Slalom -Tiny Toon Adventures (the status bar was off by one scan line before) -Mega Man 3 (displays same glitchy lines as real hardware) -Every Namco 163 game (scanline counter was broken)

finally got the mmc3 scanline counter to both pass blargg's tests and run mega man 3, but I did have to add yet another method to the mapper class to do it. (Just reading if the PPU is off broke the MMC5 counter instead.) Now to fix every other mmc3-based mapper.
fixed mmc5 ExGrafix mode

Fixed CPU cycle counters on certain mappers (most notably N106) since I had forgotten about the method that clocks those. I need to go through and check exactly which method every mapper scanline counter is using. Also tried to clean up the PPU code a bit, still a mess
Fixed Slalom and Marble Madness. Unneeded old Sprite 0 code was causing sprite 0 hit to fire too late. Up to one line too late even. Still need to fix namco mapper scan line counter

Moved more files around to fit into packages better Ran a code quality plugin, fixed at least one very obvious bug I should have found years ago and another that probably only happens in Turkey. Still a lot more to go on that. I need to commit more often.
Fixed NMI timing and VBlank flag behavior (passes all but 2 of Blargg's tests)

More PPU timing fixes Fixed VBlank flag being set twice in two different places Changed a couple more timings to match the diagram on NESDev Added skipped PPU clock on odd frames Note: there are 2 different naming conventions for the PPU cycles on the nesdev wiki: the old one obtained through experimentation and the new one from actually decapping the PPU and simulating in Visual 2A03. I'm trying to follow the new naming convention here.

Part three of timing rewrite. Turns out that most games really don't like it when every single instruction takes one more clock cycle than it should. Who knew? Also fixed location of sprite 0 hit. Anyway, now compatibility is (mostly) back where it was before. And that's good enough for one day.
